lease/financing payment.  An off-balance sheet financing with a Canadian=20
resident financial institution would eliminate this tax inefficiency, and=20
this is what I was referring to when I indicated some work may still be=20
required to restructure the turbine financing.  The withholding tax if we=20
keep this structure will total roughly C$ 500,000 over all of the=20
lease/financing payments (Chris Calger has the exact figure).  Any decision=20
to change the structure should have regard to these costs and the transactio=
n=20
costs and fees associated with finding a new Canadian resident off-balance=20
sheet lender.  In addition, if we decide to keep the turbines, or sell or=20
transfer the turbines to ENA or a third party (depending on commercially wha=
t=20
it is we decide to do with them), additional work may be required to take=20
title to the turbines, or to assign/restructure the West LB financing and th=
e=20
New Brunswick Power purchase agreement.  I am confident that the bulk of=20
commercial legal work for any of these transactions can be handled=20
internally, but that the tax legal work may require the input of outside=20
counsel.

